# Walker-Wit Integration

How the nomos walker and the wit intelligence prototype converge.
Not yet implemented — this is the design thesis.


## The Convergence

The wit prototype (now compact/src/) built a standalone intelligence:
tokenize → derive coordinates → field lookup → generate. Every
component maps to something the walker already does:

  wit component    walker equivalent
  ─────────────    ────────────────────────────
  tokenize.h       wave byte encoding (in walker)
  derive.h         coordinate IS the wave byte
  field.h          JIT cache + density histogram
  attention.h      RC decay over pipeline register
  bonds.h          bond dispatch (in walker)
  morpheme.h       affix = coordinate delta (walk op)
  generate.h       reverse lookup from ƒ evaluation


## What Dissolves

  ρ (pipeline)     IS the polynomial — not a separate accumulator
  ƒ (equation)     IS the embedding — not learned weights
  bond dispatch    IS query understanding — not mode routing
  walk bytes       ARE tokens — not separate tokenization
  RC decay         IS attention — not a learned mask
  reverse index    IS the JIT cache — not a separate index


## Remaining Gap

The walker processes coordinates. Intelligence needs:
1. A density map (what coordinates have been seen, how often)
2. A transition map (what follows what at shell 1)
3. Reverse lookup (given target coordinate, find content)

These three = the "field." The only state intelligence carries.
Everything else is stateless evaluation.

Total field size: ~58 KB hot path. Compare: GPT-4 ≈ 1.8 TB.


## Implementation Path

1. Born-index walk bytes from text input
2. Walk the bytes through the walker
3. ρ accumulates the polynomial
4. At generation point: evaluate residual, reverse lookup
5. Field updates as one-pass histogram (no training)

The intelligence IS the walker with a field. No separate system.
